{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930102601/0006.xml":{"full_text":"DEPRESSION HELD\nAT \u2018DARKEST HOUR\u2019\nPrivate Agencies Now Ready\nto Face Facts and Lift\nNation\u2019s Load.\nBY WILLIAM HARD.\nA lot of A-l economic sharps here this\nWeek end are of the expressed opinion\nthat in the matter of unemployment and\nthe business depression the country is\nnow on the brink of the good old dark\nest hour before the dawn.\" They based\nthis opinion on a proposition which is\nlargely psychological. They note that\nthe depression of 1920 and 1921 did not\nend till the country got tired of cuss\ning the Government for its troubles and\nalso got tired of thinking that its\ntroubles were bubbles which the Gov\nernment could blow away. Therefore,\nIt did not end until late in 1921, the\ncountry itself got busy and rolled up its\nsleeves and started manufacturing odd-\nJobs of any and every possible sort for\n\u202211 of the needy in every State and\ncounty and city and village and from\nthe Atlantic to the Pacific and from the\nCanadian line to the Mexican border.\nEverybody Faces Facta Frankly.\nFor the first time in the course of this\ncurrent business depression a similar\nawakenment. both pessimistic and ulti\nmately optimistic, is noted now. Pes\nsimism is that now just about everybody,\nfrom the President down, faces the full\nfacts frankly and realizes thoroughly\nthat we are undergoing not the simple\naftermath of a mere New York stock\nmarket crash, but the major final crisis\nof world-wide business uiiset consequent\nupon the great war. The best economic\njudgment here now classifies the de\npression of 1920 and 1921 and the cur\nrent depression as follows:\nThe first one was the post-war \"dis\nlocation crisis.\u201d The present one is the\npost-war \"readjustment crisis.\u201d Th%\nfirst one was a cramp. The present one\nIs worse than a cramp and also better.\nIt is a great big growing pain, after\nwhich the patient is expected to bound\nout of his post-war cradle pretty well\nreally grown up.\nThat is the dominant interpretation\nhere today and it goes along with the\npolicy which has recalled Col. Arthur\nWoods to Washington to repeat the un\nemployment relief measures which he\nforwarded in 1921 with country-wide\nsuccess. Col. Woods states to this\nwriter that his methods now will be\nsubstantially the same as his methods\nwere then. That being so. this writer\nstates as his own deduction, drawn out\nof his recollections of Col Wood's\nmethods in 1921 and drawn out of his\nobservations also of present tendencies\nIn Washington, that the following\nthings are going to happen:\n1 Much less will be heard of Federal\npublic works\" as a solution of unem\nployment\nPublic Works to Leave Spotlight.\nS. Much less will be heard even of\nState and local \"public works\" as a so\nlution of unemployment \"Public\nworks\" will continue to be pressed with\nall possible vigor as a factor in the so\nlution of the problem, but they will re\ncede from the center of the spotlight.\n3. The calcium glare will be turned\non the unemployment relief which can\noe furnished through jobs created by\nthe hundreds of thousands of separate\nprivate producing business firms and\nthe millions of separate private con\naumlng households in the country's\nmultitudinous local communities.\nThe A best figures here obtainable\n(collected by the Hoover and Shaw\nCommittee on Recent Economic\nChanges* show that In recent pros\nperous times the pay roll of wages and\nrle s for employed people in the\nunited States was running up above\nMi billion dollars a year, not million,\nbillion.\nIt is realized that no feasible expan-\nBon of \"public works\u201d can effectively\nnil the deep dent made by a major\ndepression in a pay roll so massive.\nMost of the dent, it is realized, will have\nto be filled by the job-finding capacity\nof the private business production and\nthe private household consumption of\ncommodities and of services of the\nprivate citizens of the country.\nThis is in timely harmony with the\nsudden emergence of local committees\nof private citizens throughout the coun\ntry for the finding and giving of jobs\nfrom and to their own neighbors. It is\nan emergence partly spontaneous, and\npartly stimulated from Washington. It\nis a belated but emphatic response, in\n6ome cases consciously, and in other\ncases unwittingly, to the request for the\norganization of such committees made\nmany months ago by the Federal Gov\nernment. The reliance which Presi\ndent Hoover places upon such commit\ntees in the execution of the task which\nhe has delegated to Col. Woods may be\nseen condensed into one fact.\nCroxton to Be Summoned.\nJust about the first man summoned I\nto Washington to convey current in\nformation about unemployment relief\nto Col. Woods is, or will be, Fred C.\nCroxton of Ohio. He has been execu\ntive secretary, or the like, of the Ohio\nState Committee on Unemployment.\nThe Pre-ident has regarded that com\nmittee as one of the best examples in\nthis country today of civic effort in con\ntribution to current public needs. It\nwas organized and developed under the\nauspices of Gov. Mvers Y. Cooper and\nof William T Blake, director of\nthe Ohio State Department of Indus\ntrial Relations. Its experience is likely\nto be widely studied and imitated\nthroughout the country within the next\nfew weeks. Mr Croxton. after he has\nconferred with Col Woods, will prob\nably travel from State to State com\nmunicating the methods and the results,\nin some details disappointing and in\nother details enormously encouraging,\nof the Ohio emergency endeavor. The\nessence of that endeavor would seem\nto he in the application of two out\nstanding principles\n1. Collaboration of private bu-lneas\nagencies on a State-wide scale.\n2. Extension of the collective ener\ngies of those agencies down into the\nsmallest organlzable local units of the\nStata.\nThe private business agencies which\ntook part in the organization of the\nOhio State Committee on Unemploy\nment were the State Bankers' Associa\ntion. the State Building Association\nLeague, the State Chamber of Com\nmerce. the State Manufacturers' As- i\ngociation. the State Council of Retail\nMerchants, the Btate Newspaper Asso\nciation. the State Federation of Labor,\nthe State Farm Bureau Federation and\nthe State Grange Each of these nine\nagencies thereupon appointed a rep\nresentative in each of the State* S 8\nsoon ties The nine different repre\nsentatives thus selected in each county\nthereupon formed a county commit\ntee Thu* the ensuing endeavor was\nState wide and local deep simultane\nously and conceitedly. The general\npolicies have been formulated in some\ndegree in a uniform manner at the top,\nand the active immediate work has\nbeen done by neighbors among nlgh\nbors st the bottom.\nAssistance Offers Four In.\nIt is precisely toward this getting\nright down to the bottom that Col.\nWoods' work during the next few\nmonths will be primarily directed. It\nhas already elicited a great outpouring\nof offers of assistance out of the whole\ncountry from among Col. Woods' old\ncollaborators of 1921. Such private\nstirrings and energizings were the\nsymptoms of the approaching ending\nof the post-war \"dislocation crisis\" nine\nyears ago. Hard-headed, old-time eco\nnomic specialists here believe that the\nsimilar shift now from \"public works\u201d\nand other governmentalism to private\nworks and ordinary American individ\nualism may foretell a similarly ap\nproaching ending this Winter of the\npresent post-war \"readjustment crisis.\u201d\nThey serenely state that we then will\nbe able to be fairly sure that tha war\nfestally ovar.\n\"BUY NOW\" CAMPAIGN FOUND\nSUCCESSFUL IN PHILADELPHIA\ni\nMovement Sponsored by Chamber of Com\nmerce Meets Witb Ready Response\nin Short Time.\nBy a Staff Correspondent of The Btar.\nPHILADELPHIA. October 25. \u2014After\none short week of experimenting with\na \"Buy-Now-foi-Prosperity\" Campaign,\nmerchants of Philadelphia appear to b>\nsatisfied that they have finally found a\npotent tonic for stimulating business\nand combating the ogre of depression\nthat gripped the mercantile establish\nments and th* manufacturing plants.\nThe slogan has worked like a charm\nThe people are buying again: money\nhas returned to circulation, and jobs\nare actually more numerous.\nLike a giant snowball, the slogan also\nhas rolled throughout the Unlt?d States\nand Canada, and in Philadelphia the\nbusiness leaders who started the ball\nrolling sav they already see a loosening\nof the purse strings of the Nation that\nportends a return to the days of pros\nperity \"before the crash.\u201d\nWashington. D. C., was one of the\nfirst cities to follow in the footsteps of\nPhiladelphia. Even before the cam\npaign began to show tangible results,\nth\u2019 Washington Chamber of Commerce\nstarted a back to prosperity drive\nadopting as its slogan \"Buy Now for\nBetter Business.\"\nAttacked From Two Angles.\nThe business men who started Phila\ndelphia buying met about weeks\nago to diagnose the ailment that had\nleft the business pulse of the city low\nand weak; that had the factories about\nthe city gasping like fish out of water,\nand that had the people with money\npiling it high into the banks, afraid to\nlet loose a single dollar.\nThey attacked the problem from two\nangled They debated whether they\nwould urge the factories to r eopen\nput their production on full thu.\nsolving the unemployment problem,\nputting money into the people s pockets\nto spend with the merchants, or whether\nthey would urge those who are making\nand banking their money to spend It\nstimulate wholesale buying and give the\nfactories orders upon which they could\nstep up the production of their plants\nand return the idle workers to their\nThey decided on the latter course\nwhen they discovered that the saving*\nand checking deposits of the bank*\nstood at the highest levels In hLstory--\nwhen they discovered that the trouble\nwith this country is not that the fac\ntories are not turning out the gcxri*.\nthat it is the fact that the people of the\ncountry have been the victims of the\npsychological effect of the stock market\ncrash of a year ago and have started\nhoarding their money and keeping it\nout of the channels of trade.\nIt was last Monday that the City of\nPhlladelphai received the first big blast\nof the \u201cBuy Now for Prosperity\" of the\ncity's Chamber of Commerce.\nPlacarded Over City.\nThe city woke up last Monday morn\ning to find \"Buy Now for Prosperity'\nplastered on all it* street cars, being\nblared at them over the radio, plastered\non the bills they received in their morn\ning mail, on the caps of the babies\u2019 milk\nbottles, drummed at them from the end\nof every motion picture in town, hurled\nat them from the store window of every\nmerchant in the city, shouted at them\nfrom the head of every luncheon meet\ning table, glaring down at them from\nevery street car, subway and elevated\nseat, plastered all over every railroad\nstation, blazing forth from the first\npage of every morning and afternoon\nnewspaper In the city, spread all over\nevery available sign board in the city\u2014\nin short, put where every man, woman\nand child In the city could see it hun\ndreds of times a day.\n\"Buy Now for Prosperity\" was dinned\nat the city of Philadelphia from every\npossible angle.\nToday George W. Elliott, execu-1\ntive secretary of the Philadelphia\nChamber of Commerce, said he had\nbeen flooded with local reports of the\nsuccess of the campaign all week and\nhad been beselged with calls from\nchambers of commerce and other busi\nness men's organizations from Canada\nto Florida, coast to coast, asking \"How\nhave you done it?\u201d\n\u201cWe were doctoring our own prob\nlem here in Philadelphia.\u201d he said, \"but\nit seems to go for the entire Nation, for\nCanada, too\u2014for the Nation is accept\ning our diagnosis and adopting our\ntreatment.\u201d\nFor three weeks, at least, that slogan\nwill be dinned at the people of Phila\ndelphia Just as steadily as when it was\nfirst started last Monday, and by that\ntime. Elliott believes, a flood of good,\nhard American dollars will be coursing\nthrough the arteries of American com\nmerce. giving the life blood to business\nthat has been its only need in the hour\nof its illness.\nTreatment Was Simple.\n\"The treatment was simple,\u201d Elliott\ndeclared today. \"Once he had dl-\nagnosed the Kliment and adopted the j\nmedicine, we called in all the organ-\n1 rations of business men in the city and\nput the problem squarely up to them j\nThey came across with subscriptions to\nfinance the campaign, and the first\nthing we knew we had the co-opera\ntion of the entire business interest of j\nthe city and the ball was rolling and\ngathering In size and momentum every\nminute. 1\n\"We found in that first conference,\nhe continued, \"that the need of Indus-\ntry and of the city merchant was the\ndollars to make the wheels go around\nand get the stock* moved from tne\nmerchant*' counter*. Reports of the\nFederal Reserve System show that the\ndeposits of the member banks in these j\ndays of depression have Increased j\n$1,494,000,000 in the last six months,\nand recent reports Indicate a gain\nof $700,000,000 in the savings deposits\nof banks throughout the country\nenough money to lubricate the wheels\nof commerce and send them rolling at\na record clip.\n\"The Philadelphia Chamber of Com\nmerce came to the conclusion that there\n1* no scarcity of dollars, but that\nthrough fear these dollars are being\nhoarded. A dollar that is idle through\nfear stop* the wheels of industry, re\nduces retail zelling by reduced con\nsumption and increases unemployment.\n\"The chamber decided this cycle\nmust be broken down\u2014that this false\npsychology that ha* stagnated industry.\nI reduced buying and caused increased\nunemployment must be dissipated.\nThis false psychology we termed 'en\nthusiastic pessimism' and it was at this\nstate of mind that we directed out at\ntention. with the result our Buy Now\nfor Prosperity' campaign.\nDollar Much Bigger.\n\"There 1* an added Incentive to this\nspending. Government statistics show\nthat the dollar buys more goods today\nthan at any time aince 1913. Prices\nare low. and the dollar that Is being\nhoarded in the checking and savings\naccounts in the banks of the Nation\nis a bigger dollar than it has been in\nmany years. It ought not to be in\nthose accounts. It ought to be moving\nfrom pocket to pocket, from till to till\n\u2014circulating in the terms of manufac\ntured goods, profits for the retailer and\nwholesaler, and wages for the un\nemployed.\u201d\nThe officials of the Philadelphia\nChamber of Commerce believe four\nweeks' Intensive campaigning will be\nenough to open wide the purse strings\nof the people of that city and atart\nthem into a normal state of buying for\nthe Christmas holiday season. If not,\nthe campaign will be continued right\non through the Christmas buying\nseason.\nThe campaign has received the in\ndorsement of prrctically every civic\nand business organ'ration in the city.\nSeveral civic clubs have pledged their\nmembers to spend S2O per month per\ncapita more than usual-ibis Winter.\nI The Federation of women\u2019s Clubs,\n1 representing 100,000 women of the city,\nhas placed Itself behind th* campaign\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., OCTOBER 26, 1930\u2014PART ONE.\nand Is urging the women of the city,\nwho do a large portion of the family\nbuying, to loosen up with their dollars\nand buy the things they need at the\nbargain prices they are being offered\nfor today.\nMinisters Help Drive.\nThe district business men's organiza\ntions have been tied in with the cen\ntral organization for the duration of the\ncampaign. The ministers of the city\nin their pulpits today are dinning the\nslogan \u201cBuy now for prosperity\u201d into\nthe ears of the members of their con\ngregations, and everywhere that the\nmessage can be sent home to the ulti\nmate consumer with money in the\nbank the Chamber of Commerce has\nendeavored to get the idea across.\nElliott is adjuring the business men\nof every city which Inquires of his\nChamber of Commerce the details of\nthe eampaign. to get right at the pes\nsimistic attitude of the buying public,\nto replace this \"enthusiastic pessimism\"\nwith a smile of optimism and \u2014most\nimportant of all\u2014with a free and easy\nhand on the purse strings.\nWOODS RECRUITS\nAIDES IN NATIONAL\nJOBLESS CAMPAIGN\n(Continued From First Page.)\nand that new projecs under the $16.-\n000.000 hospitalization program author\nized by Congress last Spring would be\nbegun as soon as possible. These would\nprovide employment for 4,500 men, he\nsaid.\n\"Not only will these projects provide\nemployment for laborers during the\nconstruction period,\" he said, \"but\nwhen they are completed they will\nnecessitate employment of professional\nmen. nurses and hospital attendant*.\nIn addition, the communities in which\nthey are located will be stimulated by\nthe business of furnishing supplies for\nthe hospitals.\"\nVeterans\u2019 Bureau Employs 455.\nAs a result of the recent enactment\nof a veterans' pension bill. Col. fjams\nsaid, the Veterans' Bureau had employed\n450 additional helpers in the clerical\ndivision. He added these would be\nretained until after the crisis, even if\nthe work of handling the thousands\nof pension claims was completed before\nit ended.\nEarly passage of a naval construction\nbill at the next Congress and approprla\ntlcas following immediately afterward\nso work on the ships may begin to re\nlieve unemployment and depression was\nadvocated today by Senator Glenn, Re\npublican, Illinois.\nAssistant Commissioner J. Henry\nS<\u2019ai.tergood of the Indian Service sent\nout an order last night to superinten\ndents of Indian reservations Instructing\nthem to take steps to provide able\nbodied Indians with work on roads and\nother reservation activities to prevent\nsuffering during the Winter.\nFamily Men to Get Work.\nUnder a plan adopted by one super\nintendent. and which was sent to all\nwith the suggestion that It be adopted\nwherever practicable, only men who\nhave families would be allowed to do\nthe work.\ni All the men who work on the road\njobs would be required to agree to take\none-half of the amount they earn at\nthe end of each week while they are\nworking, with the balance to be re\nl t&lned by the superintendent and paid\nj them after the first of January.\nDYSON BURIAL RITE\nSET FOR TUESDAY\nBear Admiral to Be Buried in\nArlington With Full Military\nHonors.\nFuneral services for Rear Admiral\nCharles W. Dyson, U. S. N.. who died\nyesterday at the Naval Hospital, will be\nheld at 2 o'clock Tuesday afternoon at\nthe Washington Cathedral. Following\nthe s rvices, the body will be interred in\nArlington Cemetery with full military\nhonors.\nAdmiral Dyson, w r ho was 68 years old.\nwas last year awarded the Distinguished\nService Medal by President Hoover for\ndesigning the propellers of the aircraft\ncarri rs Saratoga and Lexington. He\nwas considered one of the world's fore-\nI most authorities on propeller designing.\nHe l* survived by his widow, Mrs.\nLillie Dyson, 1840 Lamont street.\n11 STATES ASK FEDERAL\nROAD FUNDS TO AID IDLE\nHighway Officials Would Have\nGovernment Release $125,000,000\nDuring Winter.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSALT LAKE CITY, October 25 \u2014Re\nguest for the release of $125,000,000 In\nFederal aid road funds to provide em-\nI ployment during the Winter in the 11\ni Western States has been made by Henry\niH. Blood, president of the Western\nAssociation of Highway Officials and\nchairman of the Utah State Road Com\nmission.\nIn a telegram yesterday to Thoinas H.\nMacDonald, chief of the Bureau of Pub\nlic Roads, in Washington, Mr. Blood\nasked that official to assist in gaining\nthe advance for the Western States. The\nfund was allotted by the Government for\n1932 Federal aid road work.\nARTS CLUB TO PRESENT\nNATIONAL PARK LECTURE\n\nDr. Harold C. Bryant to Discuss:\nScenic Beauties of Public\nPlaygrounds.\nThe Arts Club will feature an illus\ntrated lecture Tuesday evening on the\nnational parks of the Eastern United\nState by Dr. Harold C. Bryant, recently\nappointed assistant 1\ndirector of the Na- I\ntional Parks Serv\nice, in charge of its\nnew branch of edu- I\ncation.\nDr. Bryant, who\nis on an Inspection\ntrip to Acadia Na-\ntional Park, will\ndeal in his lecture I\nwith the scenic;\nbeauties of Acadia\nand Great Smokies j\nNational Parks and\nthe areas of the\nI Everglades and\nI Shenandoah Na\ntional Parks, the\nlast being within\n90 miles of the\nDr. Srst\u00dft.\nCapital and containing the President\u2019*\nRapidan camp.\nBankruptcy Petition It Filed.\nJoseph M Parker, jr.. a clerk In the\nDistrict Building, residing at 312\nSecond street southeast, has filed a\nCtlon to be adjudged bankrupt. He\ni his debts at $2,715.11 with no\nassets. He is represented by Attorney\nR. R. Hilton.\nBANKERS APPROVE\nIBUY-NOW CAMPAIGN\nSavings Pile Up That Could\nBe Put Into Channels of\nCommerce.\nThe \"buy-now-for-better-buslness\u201d\ncampaign of the Washington Chamber\nof Commerce yesterday received the\nwhole-hearted support of leading bank\ners of the city, who declared that the\ntills of the local banks are piled high\nwith both savings and checking ac\ncounts. that treed into the channels of\nwholesale and retail trade will go a\nlong way toward relieving business de\npression in this section and reducing\nunemployment to the minimum.\nThere are in the banks here, they\nsaid, ample funds for any expansion In\nthe purchase of merchandise advocated\nby the Chamber of Commerce\u2014funds\nthat fear of the depression caused de\npositors to pile up in the banks to un\nusually high levels.\nIntensive Drive Planned.\nThe buy-now-for-better-business cam\npaign will get an impetus from an in\ntensive drive on November 2 through\nthe churches and newsjApers of the\ncity. George A. G. Wood, president of\nthe Washington Gas Light Co., who\nfirst proposed the plan to the chamber,\nis chairman of the Campaign Com\nmittee. Four other members of the\nchamber are included on the com\nmittee. which it is proposed to expand\nlo Include members of the clergy and\nof the press. i\nThe recent call of the controller of\nthe currency, John W. Pole, showed 1\nthat the Washington banks had added\nmore than *10.000.000 to their deposits\nsince the New York Stock Market crash\nlate last year. The local banks gained\nmore than *3.500.000 between the\ncontroller's calls of June 30, 1930, and\nSeptember 24, according to an official\ntabulation.\nIn answer to the last condition call,\nthe 22 savings banks in Washington\nreported total deposits of *41,748.583.63.\na gain of *569.407 over the figures of\nJune 30. The national banks reported\na gain of *3.260.221 over the June state\nment, and as all these banks have sav\nings departments, indications are also\nevident here of some sharp gains in\nsavings. Tiust company figures were\nnot so good, but these banks report a\nbroad interest in thrift and a steady\ngrowth in savings.\nChristmas Fund Large.\nThe Christmas Savings Clubs, which\nare maintained by nearly all the banks\nin Washington, will pay out some\n*7.000,000 in December. It is estimated\nby bankers that more than 50 per cent\nof this sum should go into trade chan\nnels, the rest into permanent bank sav\nings and payment of bills.\nEliot H. Thomson, a local banker,\nhas compiled statistics which show\nthat Washington's half-million citizens\nhave an average \"spending income\u201d of\n*1.328, compared with *1,290 for New\nYork, *1,102 for Chicago and *862 for\nPhiladelphia. He also calls attention to\nthe purchasing power of the 1930 dollar, i\nwhich will go farther than the 1929\ndollar on account of lower prices.\nLanier P. McLachlen, president of the\nDistrict Bankers' Association, declared\nyesterday that wise spending is vital to\nthrift and prosperity. \"The situation\nin Washington is economically sound.\u201d\nhe said. \"Business will proceed along\na normal course, unemployment prob\nably will gradually diminish, and pros\nperity will replace depression just as\nsoon as fear is eliminated from the\npublic consciousness and pocketbooks\nare opened with less reluctance. There\nis real thrift in wise spending.\u201d he\nadded.\nThat buying is already Improving in\nWashington Is revealed in the latest\nmonthly repoit of the Federal Reserve\nBank of Richmond, covering the fifth\nFederal Reserve district. This report\nstates that sales in the whole district\nwere 20 per cent ahead of August, this\nyear, and 9 per cent under September.\n1929. Sales in Washington department\nstoies were only 4.2 per cent below Sep\ntember a year ago and for the first\nnine months of this year were only 1.8\nper cent below the corresponding period\nin 1929.\n\nADVOCATES U. S. LOANS\nFOR MUNICIPAL WORKS\nBurlington, N. C., Mayor Wires\nRecommendation to Hoover Un\nemployment Relief Group.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBURLINGTON, N. C., October 25\nLoans at a low rate of Interest from the\nNational Treasury to municipalities for\nconstruction work were suggested today\nby Earl B. Horner, mayor of Burlington,\nas a means of unemployment relief.\nHU suggestion was forwarded to Presi\ndent Hoover's Unemployment Relief\nCommittee.\nHe said the credit should be extended\nonly to cities and towns constructing\nrevenue-producing utilities.\n\"By the time these loans should be\nretired.\u201d he said, \u201csuch an arrangement\n1 would see these utilities at their peak\nin production.\n\u2018\u2018lt would reduce taxes, both na\ntionally and locally.\u201d\nMcADOO IN ATLANTA\nFinishes First L>eg of \u201cBusiness\nMan\" Hop Across Nation.\nATLANTA. Ga October 25 (JP\\.\u2014For\nmer Secretary of the Treasury William\nG. McAdoo landed at Candler Field at\n2:45 p.m.. central standard time, to\nday, successfully completing the first\nleg of his transcontinental \"business\nman\" flight from New York to Cali\nfomla.\nTHE ASH CAN\nFOREVER!\ni\nby installing a\ni iSVPDDDDBWSI\nI A I 111 f OU| f u\nOIL BURNER\nThm Ckumputt Fully\nA utomatie Hmmt\nIi \u00bbIH banish dust ai.d dirt from\nyour home givs you clean,\nhealthful atmosphere In which to\nlive Ouiekly Installed and\ne-sily financed on our tl-fe-red\npvn.ect plan.\n.D?Miy~nc\nPLAN OPEN HOUSE\nFOR ANNIVERSARY\nFriends and Neighbors Are\nInvited to Settlement\nCelebration.\nNeighborhood House will hold \u201copen\nhouse\u201d on November 5 in honor of its\ntwenty-ninth anniversary.\nFriends and neighbors have b?en in\nvited to Join in the program at the set\ntlement house, 470 N street southwest,\nand exhibits will show how the settle\nment has been a real \"neighbor\" to\nhundreds of men and women and thou\nsands of children in its 29 years of work.\nBoasts Fine Traditions.\nNeighborhood House boasts of some 1\nfine traditions. It was founded in 1901 1\nby Mrs. Charles Weller, whose husband\nwas the first general secretary of the\nAssociated Charities. Their home at\n456 N street southwest became the\nneighborhood social center. There were\nno salaries, no volunteers, no Finance\nCommittee. The people simply liked the\nWellers and came visiting. That built\nup the center.\nMr. and Mrs. J. P. S. Nelight, the lat\nter head resident of the settlement, took\ncharge in 1906. Mrs. Alice P. Barney\nhad Just bought the house at 468 N\nstreet southwest for an Arts and Crafts\nBuilding and the Nelighs moved into the\nrented house vacated by the Wellers,\nusing the two houses for settlement\nwork. In 1911 Mrs. Barney bought the\nhouse at 470 N street, merging the two\ninto one building and placing the set-\nI tlement under one roof. In 1913 Miss\nEllen A. Vincent purchased the two\nhouses at 466 and 466' 2 N street south\nt\nFurniture\nadds New CHARM\nBedroom\n/Oy have taken the three groups and the several\nl J single pieces named below because they are\nrepresentative of the charm, the fine design, the\nexcellent workmanship and the moderate\nprice you will find in the furni\nture on our floors.\nA Colonial suite of seven pieces in mahogany with full site'bed is *350\nThe Directoire, an piece group in becchwood with twin beds is *475\nJUCobcUU in design is this 8 piece group in chestnut with twin beds at *6 75\nBoudoir Chairs in covers of chintz, damask or brocatelle are from *35\nLouis XV Powder Table of F ench walnut is \u201875\nColonial Powder Table in mahogany *SO\nSalem Che in mahogany with four full size drawers, is *lls\nA Block Front Ghes in maple has four full width drawers and is *125\nA Four Poster Colonial Bed in mahogany 3'-3\" or 4'*6\" wide is *25\nAn Early American Four Poster Bed m mahogany is *45\nAnother Early American Four Poster in cherry and map is *6O\nW. J. SLOANE j\n709 TWELFTH STREET. N. W.\nWASHINGTON, D. C\nI ZZ -U\nwest, enlarging the quarters to their\npresent size.\nOrganization of the first Summer\nOutings Committee took place at Neigh\nborhood House. The first public play\nground in America was established at\nNeighborhood House. The Playground\nAssociation of America, which has since\ngrown to such vast proportions, was or-\nganlzed there. The first milk station\nand the first Infants\u2019 and children's\nclinic outside h hospital was formed at\nthe settlement house.\nToday the settlement has an average\nvisiting list of 200 persons, adults and\nchildren, daily.\nOn November 5 the new' nursery will\nbe on display: the junior kindergarten\nwill give a demonstration: the bovs'\nclub. In new togs, will be on hand: the\ngirls' club will bake and sew and weave:\nthe Neighbors' Club will serve lwnch:\nthe Woman\u2019s Club will serve dinner;\nthe music department will give a pro- j\ngram: the art department will have an 1\nexhibition; and the office will furnish\ninformation and guides.\nThe celebration will be an all-day af\nfair.\nW. C. T. U. WILL PRESENT\nPLAY HERE NEXT MONDAY\nj I\n\"Protection.\u201d a play by O. O. Christ-\ngau, will be presented by citizens of\nI Washington, under the auspices of the\nWoman's Christian Temperance Union,\nnext Monday evening at the Calvary 1\nI Baptist Church.\nI O. G. Christgau, the story's author,\nwill play a leading role in the pres\nentation. while all other parts will be\nplayed by Washingtonians. Members\nlof the cast are Irvin N. Day, W. H. 1\nWadleigh. E B. Dunford. Ben Spence, I\nCharles Windle. W. B. Beilin, Dan j\nParker. Byron Kyle. Mrs. Arthur Adel\nman, Oliver Banks. Rev. Thomas Da\nvis, Charles Grandfield, Myrta Lewis.\nMrs. O. Bell. Mrs. R. Hoage, Mrs. Rich\nard Boss. Mary BenhofT, Alvin Day,\nCharles Mendel. A. C. Proctor, Mrs.\nWilliam Rich. Bart Pigman, Mrs. W. H. j\nWadleigh and Russell BenhofT.\nY. M. G A. Leader\nDR. HUBER W HURT.\nWILL WATCH BICYCLISTS\nPolice Receive Complaints of\nNumerous Ordinance Violations.\nAn order notifying precinct captains\nto instruct members of their command\nto enforce regulations governing the\noperation of bicycles was issued yester\nday afternoon by Maj. Henry\u2019 G. Pratt,\nsuperint?ndent of police.\nNumerous complaints have been made\nto police about bicyclists riding at night\nwithout lights, falling to observe .stop\nsigns at street intersections and disre\ngarding virtually all other regulations\nmade for the prot'etion of pedestrians,\naccording to Ma.i Pratt.\nA-5\nSCOUT LEADERS OPEN\nANNUAL CONFERENCE\nDr. H. W. Hurt to Speak at To\nday! Session on \u201cThe Re\nsponse* of the Boy.\u201d\n\"The Resources of the Boy'* will be\nthe .subject of an addresse delivered by\nDr Huber W Hurt of New York City,\nat the third annual conference of Boy\nScout leaders at the Y M. C A. Build\ning. opening this afternoon and continu\ning tomorrow. Other addresses and\nspecial features will constitute the pro\ngram. Several hundred Scout leadera\nfrom the District and nearby Virginia\nand Maryland troops are expected to\nattend.\nEdwin L. Maschmeyer. 411 Peabody\nstreet. Scoutmaster of Troop 79. will be\nawarded the Scoutmaster's Key, In\nrecognition of five years' effective lead\nership.\nReserve Commission Given.\nCommissionos in the Reserve Corps\nof the Army have been issued by the\nWar Department to Joachim Thode,\nf>34 Twentieth street, as a lieutenant\ncolonel of Infantry, and to Ernest A.\nGraves. *135 New Hampshire avenue,\nas a first lieutenant of Infantry.\nFOR RENT\n2 Rooms, Kitchen, Bath\nami Reception Room\nElectric Refrigeration\nReasonable Rental\nThe Argonne\nlbth and Columbia Road N. W.","height":"25551","width":"19995"}}
